{{Infobox cricket ground | ground = Cobham Park | image = | caption = | location = [[Cobham, Kent]] | coordinates = {{Coord|51.394|N|0.418|E|type:landmark|display=title, inline}} | home club = | established = 1792 | last used = 1879 }} '''Cobham Park''' near [[Cobham, Kent|Cobham]], [[Kent]] and located within the grounds of the [[Cobham Hall]] estate, was used a [[cricket]] ground. It was used as the venue for a single [[first-class cricket]] match between [[Kent county cricket teams|a team representing Kent]] and [[Hampshire county cricket teams|a Hampshire side]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/2370_f.html First-Class Matches played on Cobham Park, Cobham], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref>
The ground was used for cricket matches by Cobham Cricket Club between the 1850s and 1870s, including a number of matches against the [[Royal Engineers Cricket Club]].<ref name=ca>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/2370_misc.html Other matches played on Cobham Park, Cobham], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref> The Hall was owned by the [[Earls of Darnley]] and a number of the family were keen cricketers. [[Ivo Bligh, 8th Earl of Darnley|Ivo Bligh]], who became the 8th Earl in 1900, captained the [[English cricket team in Australia in 1882–83|first English tour of Australia in 1882–83]], recapturing [[The Ashes]].<ref name=cricketer17>Tennant I (2017) Ivo on Ivo, ''The Cricketer'', vol 15, no.2, November 2017, pp.59–61.</ref>
The hall was last used for cricket in 1951.<ref name=ca />
