'''Kinesiophobia''' is a term used in the context of [[physical medicine and rehabilitation|rehabilitation medicine]] and [[physical therapy]] to describe people's fear of pain due to movement, a factor that hinders rehabilitation and actually prolongs disability and pain.<ref>Vincent HK, et al. Outpatient rehabilitation outcomes in obese patients with orthopedic conditions. Eur J Phys Rehabil Med. 2013 Jun;49(3):419-29. Review. {{PMID|23736903}} [http://www.minervamedica.it/en/freedownload.php?cod=R33Y2013N03A0419 Free full text]</ref><ref>Czuppon S, et al Variables associated with return to sport following anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction: a systematic review. Br J Sports Med. 2014 Mar;48(5):356-64. Review. {{PMID|24124040}} [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3975129/ free full text]</ref><ref>Flanigan DC, et al. Psychological Factors Affecting Rehabilitation and Outcomes Following Elective Orthopaedic Surgery. J Am Acad Orthop Surg. 2015 Sep;23(9):563-70.  Review. {{PMID|26195567}}</ref><ref>Monticone M, et al. Cognitive-behavioural treatment for subacute and chronic neck pain. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 May 26;(5):CD010664. Review. {{PMID|26006174}}</ref><ref>Zdziarski LA, et al Chronic pain management in the obese patient: a focused review of key challenges and potential exercise solutions. J Pain Res. 2015 Feb 9;8:63-77. Review. {{PMID|25709495}} [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4332294/ Free full text]</ref><ref>Smith BE, et al An update of stabilisation exercises for low back pain: a systematic review with meta-analysis. BMC Musculoskelet Disord. 2014 Dec 9;15:416. Review. {{PMID|25488399}} [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4295260/ free full text]</ref><ref>Urquhart DM, et al.  Are cognitive and behavioural factors associated with knee pain? A systematic review. Semin Arthritis Rheum. 2015 Feb;44(4):445-55. Review. {{PMID|25151034}}</ref> This fear of movement can be a factor in increased time to return to participation in pre-injury activities. It has been shown that higher levels of kinesiophobia are linked to a lack of re-entry into pre-injury activities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Flanigan|first=David C.|last2=Everhart|first2=Joshua S.|last3=Pedroza|first3=Angela|last4=Smith|first4=Tyler|last5=Kaeding|first5=Christopher C.|date=August 2013|title=Fear of reinjury (kinesiophobia) and persisten knee symptoms are common factors for lack of return to sport after anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/254263531_Fear_of_Reinjury_Kinesiophobia_and_Persistent_Knee_Symptoms_Are_Common_Factors_for_Lack_of_Return_to_Sport_After_Anterior_Cruciate_Ligament_Reconstruction|journal=The Journal of Arthroscopic and Related Surgery|volume=29|issue=8|pages=1322–1329|doi=|pmid=|access-date=September 19, 2016|via=}}</ref>

